Headlines.BodyHeadline: Coca-Cola To Acquire Great Plains Bottling For $360 Mln

Headlines.Author: Nathalie Tadena
Headlines.Headline: Coca-Cola To Acquire Great Plains Bottling For $360 Mln

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Coca-Cola Co. KO agreed to acquire Great Plains Coca-Cola Bottling Co. for about $360 million, a move the soda titan hopes will further cut costs. The deal is expected to close by the end of the year. Great Plains, which is the fifth-largest independent Coca-Cola bottler in the U.S., has territories in Oklahoma and Arkansas. It will become an operating unit within Coca-Cola Refreshments, a Coke wholly owned subsidiary. Last year, Coke completed the acquisition of the North American operations of its biggest bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Coca-Cola To Acquire Great Plains Bottling For $360 Mln

Headlines.Author: Nathalie Tadena
Headlines.Headline: Coca-Cola Enterprises 3Q Net Up 37%; Co Raises Full-Year View

PARAGRAPH.#text: Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.'s CCE third-quarter profit rose 37% as the bottling company recorded higher revenue, though volume edged up slightly. The company raised its full-year earnings outlook to $2.14 to $2.18 a share, from its prior view of earnings of $2.10 to $2.15 a share. It continues to see revenue growth in a mid-single-digit range. It's the fifth quarter since Coca-Cola Co. (KO) wrapped up its $12 billion acquisition of CCE's North American operations. The company, which now consists of European operations, is Coca-Cola's third-biggest independent bottler.

Headlines.Author: Kristina Peterson
Headlines.Headline: US Stock Futures Stuck In Red After Trade Data

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kristina Peterson Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--U.S. stock futures weakened Friday as the U.S. trade gap widened in December, jitters over Egypt boosted crude-oil prices and the dollar and Nokia plummeted in the wake of a new corporate partnership. Dow Jones Industrial Average futures shed 27 points to 12167, while Standard & Poor's 500-stock futures fell 4 points to 1315 and Nasdaq 100 futures shed 3 points to 2359. Prior to the data, Dow futures had been down 27 points, while S&P 500 futures were off 4 and Nasdaq 100 futures shed 4 points.

Headlines.Author: Deborah Levine
Headlines.Headline: BOND REPORT: Treasurys Extend Loss After 10-year Auction

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Deborah Levine Treasury prices dropped on Tuesday, weakening after briefly paring an earlier decline following the U.S. government's auction of 10-year notes. Though the 10-year sale received strong demand, especially from a group that includes foreign investors, traders worried about the potential demand for Wednesday's sale of 30-year Treasury bonds. Yields on the current 10-year notes (UST10Y), which move inversely to prices, rose 9 basis points to 2.65%. A basis point is 0.01%. Yields on 2-year notes (UST2YR) jumped 4 basis points to 0.44%, a reversal from a session low of 0.38% earlier.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: BOND REPORT: Treasurys Extend Loss After 10-year Auction

Headlines.Author: Deborah Levine
Headlines.Headline: BOND REPORT: Treasurys Turn Lower Before 10-year Auction

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Deborah Levine Treasury prices turned lower on Tuesday, sending yields up slightly, before the U.S. government's auction of 10-year notes. Yields on the current 10-year notes (UST10Y), which move inversely to prices, rose 1 basis point to 2.56%. A basis point is 0.01%. Yields on 2-year notes (UST2YR) stood little changed at 0.40%,  retracing back from 0.38% earlier. The Treasury Department will accept bids on $24 billion in the benchmark securities until 1 p.m. Eastern time. The 10-year auction "will be a highlight in an otherwise quiet week of data releases," said strategists at RBS Securities.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: BOND REPORT: Treasurys Turn Lower Before 10-year Auction

Headlines.Author: William L. Watts
Headlines.Headline: BEFORE THE BELL:US Stock Futures Up, Dollar Drops After G-20

PARAGRAPH.#text: By William L. Watts A pledge by finance officials from the Group of 20 nations to avoid competitive currency devaluations helped lift U.S. stock-index futures Monday. Futures on the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 58 points to 11148 while futures on the Standard & Poor's 500-share index advanced 7.8 points to 1188.50. Nasdaq 100 futures gained 11 points to 2115. "There's a degree of hope that after the weekend's G-20 meeting, the world's major economies will now shy away from pursuing competitive currency devaluations and this should offer further confidence for equities across the board, although it has done little to support the dollar," said Chris Weston, research analyst at IG Markets.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: BEFORE THE BELL:US Stock Futures Up, Dollar Drops After G-20
